All Things Logistic Regression

Brian Carter

Wednesday, June 10, 2015

This document details a working example of Logistic Regression in R, using a wide array of packages, interpretation of model outputs, measures of model performance and visualisations. It is created using RMarkdown and Knit to generate the HTML. It is a work in progress and is being added to over time.

The data being used is the Statlog Heart Disease dataset taken from UCI Machine Learning Repository: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Statlog+%28Heart%29

df<-read.csv(file="Data/heartdisease.csv",header=TRUE)

Bring in some ggplot or shiny here? How to stop geom_smooth creating two regressions?

library(ggplot2)
ggplot(df,aes(x=age,y=cholest,color=as.factor(sex)))+
    geom_point(shape=1,size=4)+                                 #Circles 
    scale_color_discrete(name='Sex of Person', 
        labels=c("Male","Female")) +                            #Change the legend title and labels.
  geom_smooth(method=lm,formula=y~x,se=TRUE)+   #Linear Regression with shaded confidence interval
  xlab("Age of Person") +
    ylab("Cholestoral Level") + 
    ggtitle("Compare Two Variables") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(face="bold"))#Change the appearance of title
